There are important **differences** between dataframes and matrices. Note especially what `Df[4]` returns compared to `Mat[4]`:

```{=html}
<div style="background:#ebf1e7;border-radius:10px;padding:16px 20px;margin-bottom:1rem;">
<strong>Key difference:</strong> For a matrix, <code>Mat[4]</code> returns the 4th element column-wise. For a dataframe, <code>Df[4]</code> returns the 4th <em>column</em>. Always use <code>Df[2,3]</code> or <code>Df.iloc[2,3]</code> for single elements.
</div>
```

Dataframes can be merged using `merge()`:

```{=html}
<div style="background:#ebf1e7;border-radius:10px;padding:16px 20px;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
<strong>merge() by default</strong> performs an <em>Inner Join</em> – only rows with matching keys in both dataframes appear in the result. Use <code>all=TRUE</code> to keep all rows (Outer Join).
</div>
```

> 💡 If you need more information on a specific function, type `?data.frame` or `help(merge)` in the Console.

